I"—9<h4 id="1-amsmath-package">1. amsmath Package</h4>

<div class="language-latex highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">\usepackage</span><span class="na">[cmex10]</span><span class="p">{</span>amsmath<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>
<ol>
  <li>If using it, be sure to load this package with the cmex10 option to ensure that only type 1 fonts
will utilized at all point sizes. Without this option, it is possible that some math symbols,
particularly those within footnotes, will be rendered in bitmap form which will result in a
document that can not be IEEE Xplore compliant!</li>
</ol>

<h5 id="11-display-a-single-equation">1.1 Display a single equation</h5>
<p>To display an eauation, you have to use the equation* or equation environment,
depending on whether you wnat the equation to be numbered or not.</p>

<div class="language-latex highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nt">\begin{equation}</span>
<span class="k">\label</span><span class="p">{</span>eu<span class="p">_</span>eqn<span class="p">}</span>
e<span class="p">^{</span><span class="k">\pi</span> i<span class="p">}</span> + 1 = 0
<span class="nt">\end{equation}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="12-displaying-long-equations">1.2 Displaying long equations</h4>
<ol>
  <li>For equations longer than a line use the multline environment, insert a
double back slash to set a point for the equation to be broken</li>
  <li>The first part will be aligned to the left</li>
  <li>The second part will be aligned to the right</li>
</ol>

<div class="language-latex highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nt">\begin{multline}</span>
p(x) = 3x<span class="p">^</span>6 + 14x<span class="p">^</span>5y + 590x<span class="p">^</span>4y<span class="p">^</span>2 + 19x<span class="p">^</span>3y<span class="p">^</span>3<span class="k">\\</span> 
- 12x<span class="p">^</span>2y<span class="p">^</span>4 - 12xy<span class="p">^</span>5 + 2y<span class="p">^</span>6 - a<span class="p">^</span>3b<span class="p">^</span>3
<span class="nt">\end{multline}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="13-piecewise-function">1.3 Piecewise function</h4>

<div class="language-latex highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nt">\begin{align}</span>
	f(x)  = 
	<span class="nt">\begin{cases}</span>
		x+5, <span class="p">&amp;</span> x&gt;0 <span class="k">\\</span>
		x-5, <span class="p">&amp;</span> x&lt;0
	<span class="nt">\end{cases}</span>
<span class="nt">\end{align}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>
<h4 id="14-split">1.4 Split</h4>
<h4 id="15-matrix">1.5 Matrix</h4>
<ol>
  <li>amsmath provides command to typeset matrices with different delimiters.</li>
</ol>

<div class="language-latex highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c">% 1. plain</span>
<span class="nt">\begin{matrix}</span>
1 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 2 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 3<span class="k">\\</span>
a <span class="p">&amp;</span> b <span class="p">&amp;</span> c
<span class="nt">\end{matrix}</span>

<span class="c">% 2. round bracket</span>
<span class="nt">\begin{pmatrix}</span>
1 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 2 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 3<span class="k">\\</span>
a <span class="p">&amp;</span> b <span class="p">&amp;</span> c
<span class="nt">\end{pmatrix}</span>

<span class="c">% 3. curly bracket</span>
<span class="nt">\begin{Bmatrix}</span>
1 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 2 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 3<span class="k">\\</span>
a <span class="p">&amp;</span> b <span class="p">&amp;</span> c
<span class="nt">\end{Bmatrix}</span>

<span class="c">% 4. square bracket</span>
<span class="nt">\begin{bmatrix}</span>
1 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 2 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 3<span class="k">\\</span>
a <span class="p">&amp;</span> b <span class="p">&amp;</span> c
<span class="nt">\end{bmatrix}</span>

<span class="c">% 5. pipes</span>
<span class="nt">\begin{vmatrix}</span>
1 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 2 <span class="p">&amp;</span> 3<span class="k">\\</span>
a <span class="p">&amp;</span> b <span class="p">&amp;</span> c
<span class="nt">\end{vmatrix}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="2-mdwmath-package">2. mdwmath Package</h4>
<ol>
  <li>mdwmath.sty which is used to format equations</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="3-graphicx-package">3. graphicx Package</h4>
<p>graphicx offers a <strong>\resizebox</strong> command to adjust an equation.</p>
<ol>
  <li>the first parameter .35 determines how much of the width youâ€™d like to take up.</li>
  <li>the ! as the second argument will preserve the aspect ratio.</li>
</ol>

<div class="language-latex highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nt">\begin{equation}</span>
